                        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m serif govuk-heading--link" id="application-view-content-custom-59-heading">3<!-- -->. <!-- -->Case for Support: public health
                            outcomes</h2>
                        <div class="serif" id="application-view-content-custom-59" style="/*overflow-x:auto*/">
                            <div>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><strong>The public health challenge and need</strong></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Chronic (persistent) breathlessness despite treatment of causal disease(s)[1] is associated with disability and a vicious
                                    cycle of avoidance of physical activity (exertion-related breathlessness), deconditioning, worse function and increasing breathlessness. People with
                                    chronic breathlessness reduce or cease activities important for individual and societal wellbeing[2] and, in high-resource countries, are more likely
                                    to use healthcare services.[5] The non-communicable diseases (NCDs) (e.g., chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD),[6] coronary heart disease,[7]
                                    lung cancer[8]) causing chronic breathlessness are common in India, and increasing, mirroring high rates of tobacco smoking, air pollution[9] and
                                    poverty.[10] Adverse impact has increased since the COVID-19 pandemic.[14]</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">The burden of NCDs falls disproportionately on people in low-resource settings, e.g, India, accounting for 80% of global
                                    COPD and asthma mortality,[10] with high levels of disability due to poor prevention, poor healthcare access, late presentation and younger
                                    onset.[15]&nbsp; In high-resource settings those affected participate less in the workforce,[3] but the younger age-profile in low-resource settings
                                    leads to profound effects on absenteeism <u>and</u> presenteeism, risking children’s education to redress income reduction, and poverty. Breathlessness
                                    strongly predicts COPD impairment in low-resource countries and is identified as a therapeutic target.[13]</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Most NCDs are incurable; the main therapeutic goal is palliation. A 2002-2003 WHO survey found 7.7% of women and 6.1% of
                                    men in India reported daily breathlessness unrelated to physical activity,[16] indicating severe symptoms.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><strong>Public health outcomes and strategic priorities</strong></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Self-management chronic breathlessness strategies could potentially address strategic public health priorities
                                    including:</p>
                                <ul class="serif govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
                                    <li>Ensuring healthy lives and promoting wellbeing for all at all ages[17]</li>
                                    <li>Promoting physical activity in sedentary older adults to improve physical and mental health[18]</li>
                                    <li>reducing workforce participation due to ill health[19]</li>
                                    <li>reducing social roles due to ill health[20]</li>
                                    <li>reducing unaffordable out-of-pocket healthcare expenditure[10]</li>
                                </ul>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">This project will co-design a programme-theory to inform development of a flexible population health, community-based
                                    education intervention. The intervention will address breathlessness-related beliefs and behaviours e.g., physical activity, cool airflow, healthcare
                                    utilisation. This will be informed by our realist review’s programme theories presented in “if, then” formats to demonstrate what works, for whom, how
                                    and where.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Future study will evaluate utility, applicability, affordability and feasibility of the intervention along with measures
                                    relating to beliefs (community influencers) and individual behaviours/clinical outcomes (physical and social activity, self-rated health and
                                    well-being, workforce and education participation, healthcare utilisation).</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><strong>Study population</strong></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><u>The study population in this proposal</u> is co-design stakeholders rather than study subjects. We will work with
                                    stakeholders to refine <u>the future study</u> population(s), raise breathlessness as a public health priority, and ensure future buy-in. Stakeholders
                                    will include clinical and public health leaders (doctors, nurses, allied health, policy influencers) and community representatives (community and
                                    faith, education, volunteers), and those with personal chronic breathlessness experience. Group composition will include different cultural/faith
                                    groups and account for gender role imbalance at work and in the home to facilitate women’s voices. Our study investigators and Partners have wide
                                    networks to facilitate key stakeholders’ invitations including Public Health Foundation India, Pallium India, and clinical/community training
                                    programmes across Indian states.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Our future aim is to implement and evaluate an intervention to improve the function of people with chronic breathlessness
                                    by challenging unhelpful, and strengthening helpful health beliefs <em>via</em> <u>a future study population</u> of community influencers likely to
                                    lever benefit for patients suitable for self-management (e.g., Accredited Social Health Activist Workers [ASHAs], these are primary healthcare
                                    promotors particularly in vulnerable communities using behaviour change communication, and facilitating access to health services).</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Our intervention is likely to be applicable to other low-resource settings; particularly to disadvantaged groups with high
                                    chronic breathlessness prevalence, e.g., older adults, greater deprivation. We will therefore also consider how this could be adapted.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <hr class="govuk-section-break govuk-section-break--l govuk-section-break--visible">
                        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m serif govuk-heading--link" id="application-view-content-custom-60-heading">4<!-- -->. <!-- -->Case for Support: evidence gap</h2>
                        <div class="serif" id="application-view-content-custom-60" style="/*overflow-x:auto*/">
                            <div>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">To our knowledge, our proposal is the first population health approach to this problem. This is necessary because of the
                                    widespread and serious nature of the chronic breathlessness (see above) and because wellbeing and lifestyle approaches have the greatest potential to
                                    address common misconceptions. Many people, for example, fear that activity is harmful; however it can reduce breathlessness by increasing fitness.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Evidence-based,[21] low-cost self-management breathlessness-targeted interventions are effective and cost-effective[22,23]
                                    and deliverable in community-settings (e.g., breathing techniques, hand-held fans, lifestyle approaches such as paced physical activity), reducing
                                    breathlessness severity,[24] breathlessness-related distress,[22,23] and increased breathlessness mastery.[25] With some components, e.g., fans,
                                    emerging evidence shows faster recovery time from exertion-induced breathlessness,[26,27] increased physical activity[28] and reduced
                                    medication.[26]These techniques require little medical knowledge; are teachable to lay workers, family carers,[25,29] and clinical support staff.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Clinical practice frameworks, such as the Breathing, Thinking, Functioning model,[30] are increasingly recognised in
                                    high-income countries.&nbsp; Conceptual frameworks such as “Breathing Space”[31] highlight how engaged coping and appropriate help-seeking and health
                                    beliefs (patient) and attention to symptom (clinician) helps maximise the patient's wellbeing, but are developed from literature from which
                                    low-resource setting data is largely absent. However, such a low-cost, community-based approach could be readily adapted to low-resource countries such
                                    as India within a population health intervention. By empowering people to make simple lifestyle changes that improve individual symptom control and
                                    function, human and social capital can be developed and healthcare needs reduced. Many components of breathlessness self-management have not been
                                    developed, or tested for utility, applicability, or feasibility in low-resource countries. Our proposed study recognises the potential relevance of
                                    interventions and clinical tools internationally to the Indian context, along with the need for contextual evaluation and modification.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">From other health interventions, we know that implementation fails unless the local context and health beliefs are
                                    understood and interventions are adapted.[32] Regarding breathlessness self-management, emerging data suggest that patients’ and clinicians’ health
                                    beliefs about cool airflow, particularly in hotter countries, may make fans less acceptable. Conversely, as shown in a recent realist review of
                                    breathing exercises in people with COPD[33] (in which 58% studies were from Asia, mostly from China), other components such as deep breathing,
                                    meditation and low-level exercise which make the connection between breathing and anxiety may be very acceptable in Asian cultures.&nbsp; However,
                                    clinicians’ management and understanding of e.g., chronic respiratory diseases in low-resource countries suffers from a lack of clinical guidelines and
                                    inclusion in educational curricula, and knowledge of breathlessness interventions may be non-existent. An Indian physician study[34] showed they
                                    recognised chronic breathlessness as a serious problem, but expressed therapeutic nihilism and helplessness to the extent they avoided the subject with
                                    their patients.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Whilst availability of pain medications is subject to strict legal and regulatory barriers, no legal barriers exist for
                                    development and roll-out of breathlessness self-management interventions, yet these remain largely un-implemented in low-resource countries.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <hr class="govuk-section-break govuk-section-break--l govuk-section-break--visible">
                        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m serif govuk-heading--link" id="application-view-content-custom-61-heading">5<!-- -->. <!-- -->Case for Support: subsequent
                            development phases</h2>
                        <div class="serif" id="application-view-content-custom-61" style="/*overflow-x:auto*/">
                            <div>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><strong>Description of the intervention</strong></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">We will develop a population health educational intervention directed at community workers, (e.g., ASHA workers; educators)
                                    who can influence people affected by chronic breathlessness. Community workers will be upskilled to address Breathlessness Beliefs and Behaviours
                                    management (“Three Bs”), including unhelpful beliefs about physical activity (“breathlessness is harmful, physical activity should be avoided”) and
                                    helpful beliefs (“meditation helps anxiety, spiritual connection and regulates breathing”) (see logic model).</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Our overarching <em>intervention</em> programme theory is that an intervention resonating with existing cultural healthy
                                    living beliefs, and working with individuals in family and community contexts, provides a stronger basis for addressing unhelpful beliefs about
                                    breathlessness management.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Our overarching <em>implementation</em> programme theory is that effective delivery is driven by alignment of the beliefs
                                    of a wide range of stakeholders, underpinned by low-cost to support delivery.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><strong>Pathway to main study and later evaluation stages</strong></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">During our co-design work (Step 2) we will conduct an evaluability assessment to agree process <u>and</u> outcome measures
                                    for the evaluative phase, including what data should/could be collected.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Our <u>subsequent work</u> (feasibility, evaluation, implementation) will follow the MRC Framework for Complex Intervention
                                    Development,[35] compatible with improvement approaches to population health interventions.[36] <em>The main evaluation phase study with in-built pilot
                                        to check recruitment rates and data quality</em> will be quasi-experimental with a parallel process evaluation to explore how context affects
                                    intervention operation.[35,37] recruiting both e.g., ASHAs and client/patients in areas where ASHA training does and does not include the “Three-B”
                                    intervention. Outcomes will have been determined in <u>this</u> proposal (Step 2) and may include ASHA beliefs and behaviours, and patient/client
                                    self-report (self-rated health, physical activity, social activity, work participation, activities of daily living, breathlessness severity, quality of
                                    life) and objective (health service utilisation, physical activity [e.g., step-count], use of breathing techniques). Consistent with a theory-based
                                    research perspective, the emphasis will be on getting a better understanding (empirically) of how the intervention is perceived, understood, used (or
                                    not) and has different outcomes in different contexts.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Our feasibility work will test the intervention and implementation programme theories about our education intervention in a
                                    sample of ASHAs, and/or other populations identified by our stakeholders (e.g., teachers, primary care clinicians), for acceptability, relevance and
                                    utility. Before/after evaluation of change in beliefs would be conducted. Depending on the study population, this might include measuring
                                    breathlessness inquiries made (increasing if beliefs that breathless is untreatable are countered). Economic modelling will be undertaken at this
                                    stage.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <hr class="govuk-section-break govuk-section-break--l govuk-section-break--visible">
                        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m serif govuk-heading--link" id="application-view-content-custom-62-heading">6<!-- -->. <!-- -->Case for Support: methodology</h2>
                        <div class="serif" id="application-view-content-custom-62" style="/*overflow-x:auto*/">
                            <div>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><strong>Summary design:</strong></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Stakeholder engagement is prioritised with Expert and Stakeholder Group members contributing throughout.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Using Li et al’s realist review of COPD breathing exercises[33] as our starting point, we will conduct an expanded
                                    <strong>realist review</strong> (step 1a) to explore all non-pharmacological self-management interventions for NCD-related chronic breathlessness to
                                    identify evidence and theory for self-management. We will develop intervention and implementation programme theory, and map intervention components to
                                    determine ‘what works, for whom’ with special consideration for low-resource settings. We will follow RAMESES publication standards.[38]</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">We will refine our programme theories using <strong>realist evaluation</strong> (step 1b) to develop content for a
                                    prototype intervention and identify contextual delivery barriers and facilitators. Parallel <strong>co-design intervention development</strong> will
                                    use the updated MRC Framework for Complex Intervention Development.[35]</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">We will deliver the content of a flexible, co-designed, population health, community-based education intervention, relating
                                    to breathlessness-related beliefs and behaviours e.g., physical activity and cool airflow, ready for feasibility-testing and evaluation. We will have
                                    defined populations who aren't thriving (breathlessness lens), and the population(s) for future study, agreeing a purpose for each with
                                    aims,&nbsp;drivers, and how to address these.[33]</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><strong>Expert and Stakeholder groups</strong></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Project Partners are the basis of our ~three-monthly <strong>Expert Group</strong> including experts in respiratory,
                                    primary and palliative care with links to community and other groups (e.g., Family Caregiver Education, Dream-A-Dream, Public Health Foundation India,
                                    Pallium India). They will be responsible for inviting stakeholders and contributing to theory development.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">We will convene ~<strong>5 stakeholder groups</strong> from across India:</p>
                                <ul class="serif govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
                                    <li>Opinion leader physicians (primary, secondary care and public health)</li>
                                    <li>nurses/allied health professionals&nbsp;(primary and secondary care)</li>
                                    <li>community, education workers, lay volunteers</li>
                                    <li>community/faith leaders or members</li>
                                    <li>people with experience of chronic breathlessness; family members</li>
                                </ul>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Stakeholder groups (~n=8 per group) will be assembled purposively from rural and urban settings with gender/culture/faith
                                    balance where appropriate. Each group will meet ~ <strong>three-monthly</strong> and be facilitated by a study team member(s) and project coordinator
                                    (interpreter available if necessary). Most will be virtual, but face-to-face (particularly community) groups can be conducted. Individuals may be
                                    interviewed if preferred.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><strong>Step 1a. Realist review</strong></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><em>Aim:</em> develop programme and implementation theory about how breathlessness self-management interventions can
                                    achieve desired impacts for different people</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><em>Methods and analysis</em></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">We will follow five steps:[39] (1) define review scope, (2) develop initial programme theories, (3) identify evidence
                                    through systematic review, (4) study selection (5) data extraction/synthesis.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">We will use a theory-based approach guided by our expert group to develop initial programme theories ahead of the
                                    systematic review, then search databases (e.g., Medline, CINAHL, Scopus, PsychInfo, EBSCO host discovery [Indian literature]), grey literature and
                                    citations of relevant studies. Data will be extracted, and synthesised iteratively. Causal links between context, mechanisms and outcomes will be
                                    mapped and low-resource relevance drawn out.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><strong>Step 1b. Realist evaluation</strong></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><em>Aim:</em> refine programme and implementation theory to produce a conceptual framework of intervention components
                                    (breathlessness techniques or behaviours) likely to help people with chronic breathlessness in India</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><em>Methods and analysis:</em> We will conduct three “rounds” of stakeholder workshops regarding preliminary programme
                                    theory and explanatory accounts of how and why existing intervention components may work in India. Following each, programme theory will be refined by
                                    the study team and presented to our expert group to develop a conceptual platform to be presented to key stakeholders for further refinement in a
                                    feedback loop.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><strong>Step 2. Intervention development</strong></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><em>Aim:</em> develop a prototype education intervention deliverable in the Indian context ahead of feasibility and
                                    evaluation of effect.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><em>Methods and Analysis:</em> Drawing on our expertise in co-designing breathlessness interventions,[40] we shall use
                                    Intervention Mapping[41,42] to involve each of our stakeholder groups in an iterative co-design process (two meetings with each group, with a final
                                    combined group at the study end) to translate theory and evidence into practical intervention components and a plan for implementing and sustaining the
                                    prototype community-based breathlessness education intervention. Consistent with stages four and five of Intervention Mapping (the earlier stages
                                    having been addressed in our Step 1), this process will include mapping intervention and implementation programme theory to intervention components,
                                    and the development of materials to support intervention delivery. Throughout, we will pay close attention to the role of power which may be by
                                    authority or credibility.[43] To structure development of potentially vast implementation aspects, we will use the Consolidated Framework for
                                    Implementation Research adapted for low- and middle-income countries (CFIR-LMIC)[44] with its focus on stakeholders’ perceptions about intervention
                                    scalability and sustainability; practice team norms and collective beliefs about working effectively together; and need for low-cost delivery.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><em>Dissemination:</em> We will publish/present findings in peer-reviewed journals and conferences. We will also prepare
                                    executive summaries for lay and professional (including policy) audiences, with infographics. Drawing on our team expertise, particularly IPCRG links,
                                    we will produce short animated intervention prototypes which will be made available on the Wolfson Palliative Care Research Centre, linking with other
                                    key sites (IPCRG etc.)</p>
                            </div>
