                        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m serif govuk-heading--link" id="application-view-content-custom-66-heading">10<!-- -->. <!-- -->Covid impact</h2>
                        <div class="serif" id="application-view-content-custom-66" style="/*overflow-x:auto*/">
                            <div>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">As for most people, our work has been disrupted in many ways. Research projects have been delayed, clinical applicants were
                                    taken away from research to undertake clinical work, challenges of data collection with social distancing/working with vulnerable groups and so on.
                                    However, the pandemic has also presented opportunities for our work in terms of: heightened public and professional understanding of breathlessness,
                                    international lesson learning and use of technology to promote collaboration.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">As a result of COVID-19, there has been a significant discourse on breathlessness as a diagnostic indicator as well as a
                                    symptom to be relieved, with associated public recognition that public health and individual health are entangled. Less positively, the pandemic has
                                    placed huge pressures on primary and community care internationally and increased the need for community-focussed public health interventions such as
                                    that we propose.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Many clinicians and people with chronic breathlessness (and disability) have had increased opportunity to access beneficial
                                    educational interventions. Health care practitioners and patients have become accustomed to the use of technology (e.g., audio-visual software) for
                                    educational purposes and for clinical care. For example, members of our team made use of webinars to disseminate training relating to symptom
                                    management to clinicians internationally (Salins, Daniel, Palat) [COVID-19 toolkit]. The International Primary Care Respiratory Group (Williams)
                                    successfully ran a Teach the Teacher training program promoting diagnosis and management of asthma and Clark/Johnson developed an educational program
                                    for online delivery for intervention training of primary care practitioners in use of a palliative care needs assessment tool. COVID-19 has therefore
                                    normalised use of the technologies which we will use to develop our intervention and, dependent upon the outcomes of our realist review, to promote
                                    equitable access and potentially increase the impact of our intervention, whilst also taking into account the populations which may be disadvantaged
                                    with regard to technology (rural, age, socioeconomic deprived [e.g, unable to afford limitless data], less access to technology support).</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Finally, the pandemic and associated use of technology has facilitated international collaboration without need for
                                    international travel. Johnson, Salins, Clark, Currow, Pearson and Daniel have strengthened methods of collaborative working by conducting a research
                                    project identifying good practice related to opioid availability in India, with Indian data collection conducted from the UK (<em>via</em> Zoom),
                                    regular online project meetings and ongoing analysis and data management using secure encrypted platforms (MS Teams).</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Overall, the COVID-19 pandemic has increased the need for our proposed project, increased opportunities for accelerating
                                    the impact of community interventions through use of technology and increased our capability as an international team to successfully deliver our
                                    proposal.</p>
                            </div>
