                        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m serif govuk-heading--link" id="application-view-content-custom-72-heading">16<!-- -->. <!-- -->Ethical implications</h2>
                        <div class="serif" id="application-view-content-custom-72" style="/*overflow-x:auto*/">
                            <div>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><strong>Governance</strong></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">We are conducting a realist evaluation with expert stakeholders and <u>not</u> research subjects. We will obtain ethical
                                    approvals from the Hull York Medical School Ethics Board (United Kingdom) and institutional approval from the Karunashraya Hospice in India. As we are
                                    not recruiting research subjects, our Indian colleagues confirm we will not require approval from the Indian Council of Medical Research.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><strong>Stakeholder groups</strong></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">We will invite professional and lay people to participate in stakeholder groups. Participation in stakeholder groups will
                                    be voluntary. Stakeholders will be provided with a study information sheet providing details of the project and the nature of their involvement;
                                    attendance will be taken as implicit consent. Lay and professional stakeholders will be given a financial token (£5/hr) of appreciation for their time
                                    in attending meetings/interviews.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">It is feasible that lay stakeholders with experience of chronic breathlessness may become upset during discussions
                                    regarding the project as it may involve relating their own limitations and impact on life due to breathlessness. We will develop support protocols to
                                    support stakeholders, offering facilities for ‘time out,’ during group meetings as well as support provided by a study team or expert group member and
                                    referral for further support through appropriate channels if required.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Medicine is a hierarchical profession in many countries irrespective of resources, but particularly so in India and other
                                    LMICs, and Indian society is patriarchal. We are mindful of the potential power imbalances between the varying stakeholders and so workshops/events
                                    will be conducted separately with stakeholders with discrete roles to ensure a wide range of views are incorporated and all stakeholders are able to
                                    speak freely. Stakeholders may be individually interviewed if they cannot make the meeting, or prefer to do so (e.g., would feel more comfortable to
                                    express views).</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">On all stakeholder groups, we will ensure appropriate gender and seniority issues are managed (e.g., we will take expert
                                    group advice as to whether our community groups should be single gender only), and we note that in India physicians are predominantly men and nurses
                                    are predominantly women.</p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body"><strong>Other potential consequences of our study</strong></p>
                                <p class="serif govuk-body">Our primary aim is to improve awareness and management of chronic breathlessness. However, people with chronic
                                    breathlessness in India may <u>not</u> <strong></strong>have had their underlying condition diagnosed or optimally managed; our project may encourage
                                    better presentation and recognition of this neglected symptom. As part of our intervention development, we will work with our Indian clinical
                                    colleagues to develop protocols that dovetail with appropriate Indian approaches for NCD diagnosis and management.</p>
                            </div>
